### if/else in Rust

The `if` keyword branches execution based on a boolean condition. Unlike many languages, `if` in Rust is an expression.

---

### Syntax

| Construct | Example |
|-----------|---------|
| if | `if condition { }` |
| if-else | `if cond { } else { }` |
| if-else if | `if a { } else if b { } else { }` |
| if let | `if let Pattern(value) = expr { }` |

---

### Using if as an Expression

```rust
// Assign based on condition
let condition = true;
let number = if condition { 5 } else { 6 };

// All branches must return the same type
let result = if x > 0 {
    "positive"
} else if x < 0 {
    "negative"
} else {
    "zero"
};

// Traditional if for side effects
if number > 10 {
    println!("Big number!");
}
```

> **Key Point:** When using `if` as an expression, all branches must have the same type. If one branch returns a value and another doesn't, the compiler will reject it.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let temperature = 25;

    let weather = if temperature > 30 {
        "hot"
    } else if temperature > 20 {
        "warm"
    } else if temperature > 10 {
        "cool"
    } else {
        "cold"
    };

    println!("The weather is {}.", weather);
}
